### Describe the bug

In my Blazor Server project, I have a JavaScript function `SetFocus(id)` that takes the `id` of an HTML element, and then sets the focus on that element.
In the event handler of a button:
- I want to make another button visible
- and then set the focus on the button that just became visible, using `js.InvokeVoidAsync("SetFocus", "editBtn")`

What happens:
- `SetFocus` finds the edit button, because i can see it is logged to the browser console
- but focus is not set on the edit button, because `<body>` remains logged to the browser console as the `activeElement`

This does not go wrong when the `EditForm.Model` always receives the same instance. But having to always use the same instance makes things more complicated because it requires keeping track of more state. In this case i want to easily revert changes by preplacing the model.

### Expected Behavior

- I expect that the `IJSRuntime` always accesses the current DOM, and not some old version (as it seems). So that in my case the focus gets set on the button on the screen.
- Probably off topic: I actually also expect a call to `IJSRuntime.InvokeVoidAsync` to force rendering (this should be built into this call). It seems really hacky that Blazor requires a preceding call to `Task.Delay()`. Even a dedicated Blazor function to force rendering would be better.

### Steps To Reproduce

*Use my example and watch the short clip I attached.*

JavaScript (code added to _Host.cshtml):

    <script>
        // display active element every second
        DisplayActive();
        function DisplayActive() {
            setTimeout(function () {
                console.log(document.activeElement);
                DisplayActive();
            }, 1000);
        }

        // set the focus on the element with the given id
        function SetFocus(id) {
            console.log("SetFocus('" + id + "')");
            var e = document.getElementById(id)
            
            console.log(e);
            e.focus();
        }
    </script>

FocusLost.razor

    @page "/focuslost"

    <h3>FocusLost</h3>

    <EditForm Model="@m.Data">
        @if (m.editing)
        {
            <button id="cancelBtn" type="submit" @onclick="m.CancelClick">Cancel</button>
        }
        else
        {
            <button id="editBtn" type="button" @onclick="m.EditClick">Edit</button>
        }
    </EditForm>

    @code {
        class MyModel
        {
            public IJSRuntime js { get; set; }
            public bool editing { get; set; } = false;
            public MyData Data
            {
                get
                {
                    return new();
                    //return original; // returning original instead of a new() fixes it
                }
            }
            private MyData original = new();

            public async Task EditClick()
            {
                editing = true;
            }

            public async Task CancelClick()
            {
                editing = false;
                await Task.Delay(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // why is this even necessary?
                await js.InvokeVoidAsync("SetFocus", "editBtn");
            }
        }
        class MyData
        {
            public string Dummy { get; set; }
        }

        MyModel m = new();
        [Inject] public IJSRuntime js { get; set; }

        protected override async Task OnParametersSetAsync()
        {
            await base.OnParametersSetAsync();
            m.js = js;
        }
    }

Failure Scenario:
- open Microsoft Edge Chromium and visit `/focuslost`
- open the Console (in the Developer Tools)
- note that the `activeElement` is shown every 1 second (by the function `DisplayActive`)
- click the Edit button on the page, so that it is replaced by a Cancel button
- click the Cancel button on the page, so that it is replaced again with the Edit button
- wait 5 seconds for Task.Delay in the event handler `CancelClick`
- observe the browser console: the message shows `SetFocus` was actually called
- observe the browser console: the next message shows that `getElementById` actually found the button element
- observe the browser console: the next message shows the `activeElement` is the `<body>` instead of the Edit button

Success Scenario:
Now try the above steps again but this time change the code, to always return the same instance of the model from the `MyModel.Data` getter:
- by replacing `return new();`
- with `return original;`

Observe that clicking the Cancel button now correctly sets the focus on the Edit button.


